{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513293"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:07:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:07:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12081"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12081"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.06,0.64,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4635"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108234"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4635"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12081"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90646"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"2757"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7026"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7033"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40319"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42704"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108234"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old woman is brought in by ambulance to the Emergency Department with a first episode of palpitations lasting 20 minutes, associated with hot flushes and nausea. She described the palpitations as pounding heartbeats which came on while she was cooking. There is no associated chest pain or dyspnoea, and her symptoms have now completely resolved. She has a medical history of hypertension, dyslipidaemia and anxiety. Her medications include enalapril and rosuvastatin. She is a non-smoker. She does not drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn physical examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her cardiovascular examination is normal. An ECG shows a heart rate of 90/min, regular rhythm, P-waves present, normal QRS complexes and prolonged PR interval in keeping with 1st-degree AV block. Blood tests, including troponin, haemoglobin, electrolytes and thyroid function, return normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance and discharge with no follow-up required","Commence beta-blocker therapy","Arrange 24 hour Holter monitoring with GP follow-up","Admit for observation of symptom recurrence","Admit for telemetry"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAs many patients present to ED while in sinus rhythm, it is important to take a thorough history including the nature, frequency, rhythm and intensity of the palpitations. In the above scenario, the palpitations have resolved spontaneously, there is no haemodynamic compromise and no other factors which point toward an acute coronary syndrome. Bloodwork is also normal and there is no indication for inpatient admission (eg. \u003Cstrong\u003Eadmission for observation of symptom recurrence\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eadmission for telemetry\u003C/strong\u003E), thus \u003Cstrong\u003Earrange 24 hour Holter monitoring with GP follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate. If required, subsequent cardiology referral could then be considered to arrange longer periods of Holter monitoring and other investigations such as echocardiogram.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassuring the patient and discharging from ED with no follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E is dangerous as though the palpitations have resolved, further work-up and investigations should be done to thoroughly assess potential underlying causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing beta-blocker therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would be premature without identifying the underlying cause of the palpitations. While beta-blockers can be useful for symptom control in certain arrhythmias, they should not be initiated without a clear diagnosis, especially in a patient with a first presentation of palpitations that have completely resolved. Additionally, beta-blockers can mask symptoms that might be diagnostically useful during Holter monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFirst degree AV block is considered a benign finding and usually does not need specific treatment. However, it is important to establish whether the palpitations were related to a transient arrhythmia that was not captured on the initial ECG, which is why ambulatory monitoring is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Though palpitations can be triggered by stress, anxiety or too much caffeine, they can be a sign of an underlying cardiac condition and should be investigated.","First-degree AV block is a condition of abnormally slow conduction through the AV node and is defined by ECG changes of PR interval \u003E200ms without atrial to ventricular conduction disruption. It is generally asymptomatic.","Ambulatory ECG monitoring is the investigation of choice for patients with intermittent palpitations to correlate symptoms with cardiac rhythm."],"references":["Probst MA, Mower WR, Kanzaria HK, Hoffman JR, Buch EF, Sun BC. Analysis of emergency department visits for palpitations (from the National Hospital Ambulatory Medical Care Survey). Am J Cardiol. 2014;113(10):1685-90. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24698469/","McLellan AJ, Kalman JM. Approach to palpitations. Aust J Gen Pract. 2019 Apr;48(4):204-209. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31256490/","McLellan A, Kalman J. Approach to palpitations. Australian Journal of General PRactice. 2019: 48 (94).  Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/april/approach-to-palpitations"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12081"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90646"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-08T19:00:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-08T19:01:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4635"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108234"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self